I had another post planned to share this afternoon, but I’m not feeling very “gram-worthy” today. I don’t want to post something like everything is fine when I’m not fine. I’ve always been very real on my account and with everyone on here. And right now, things are hard. Things suck. Covid sucks. What’s happening around the world sucks. It’s sucks the life out of you. It sucks the joy out of what should bring you joy.

And instead of hiding those feelings, I’m posting them here. Because I know I’m not the only one feeling this way. And because I don’t want someone else to think they’re the only one, either.

I’m acknowledging my feelings. I’m acknowledging that the things that are happening just suck right now. But I’m not going to stay in this place. I’m going to do the things that help me come out of these feelings- talking to a friend; pulling out art supplies, going for a run… things that bring me joy.

And if that’s you today too. If you’re in the same space, please know you’re not alone. Please feel what you need to feel, but don’t stay here. Reach out to someone (it can be me). Remember what brings you joy and spend some time today doing that. Take care of yourself today. You deserve it.

How fantastic are the stairs at my daughter’s school??? This is such a fun idea and such a unique way to help students learn their multiplication facts! What else can you think of that would be great for this spot?
.
.
.

I. HAVE. MISSED. THIS.
Students.
In seats.
With markers.
And manipulatives.
This small group is working on tape diagrams and equivalent ratios. The Gen Ed teacher and I are co-teaching the lesson, and then I’m differentiating (with the use of manipulatives) and accommodating (with the use of the multiplication chart).

And for the first time… in almost 18 months… I feel like I’m back to doing what I do best. I just want to teach kids. I want to help new concepts make sense. I want the lightbulb moments. And this lesson? It gave me that feeling again. And I HAVE MISSED THIS!!
.
.

node.text:
Sometimes, you find a film that speaks to you as an educator, a parent, and a human being. #ConfettiMovie is that film for me. Thanks to Dada Films for allowing me to watch @confettimovie before its release in theaters this Friday, August 20th. Swipe for the trailer.

Synopsis: Meimei is considered an outcast in her school in China after learning she has dyslexia (as do 1 in 10 people worldwide). Meimei and her mother embark on an international journey from China to New York, where Meimei’s mother will stop at nothing to ensure her daughter receives everything she needs and is seen as the amazing child she really is.

We can’t “take it off.” If a student honestly doesn’t need an accommodation anymore, that’s wonderful! After all, that’s the GOAL! But it’s not something that can just be done. It needs data to support it from progress monitoring. It needs a full IEP meeting with the whole team (teachers, service providers, parent, and student) being in agreement. Remember, an IEP is a legal document that must be followed as it’s written. It can be amended and updated, but not on a whim.
.
.
.

Progress monitoring is essential when it comes to tracking student progress to determine if interventions and accommodations are working or need to be revised. I usually do progress monitoring for academics once a week, and i track the scores/reports in my digital sped binder. Here, I’m covering my two biggest tips for progress monitoring in the classroom. Drop your questions in the comments, and let’s keep the conversation going!
